        <infon key="n">1</infon>
        <offset>0</offset>
        <text>A multitrophic model to quantify the effects of marine viruses on microbial food webs and ecosystem processes
</text>
      </sentence>
    </passage>
    <passage>
      <offset>110</offset>
      <infon key="type">body</infon>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">2</infon>
        <offset>110</offset>
        <text>Viral lysis of microbial hosts releases organic matter that can then be assimilated by nontargeted microorganisms.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">3</infon>
        <offset>225</offset>
        <text>Quantitative estimates of virus-mediated recycling of carbon in marine waters, first established in the late 1990s, were originally extrapolated from marine host and virus densities, host carbon content and inferred viral lysis rates.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">4</infon>
        <offset>460</offset>
        <text>Yet, these estimates did not explicitly incorporate the cascade of complex feedbacks associated with virus-mediated lysis.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">5</infon>
        <offset>583</offset>
        <text>To evaluate the role of viruses in shaping community structure and ecosystem functioning, we extend dynamic multitrophic ecosystem models to include a virus component, specifically parameterized for processes taking place in the ocean euphotic zone.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">6</infon>
        <offset>833</offset>
        <text>Crucially, we are able to solve this model analytically, facilitating evaluation of model behavior under many alternative parameterizations.
</text>
      </sentence>
      <sentence>
        <infon key="n">7</infon>
        <offset>974</offset>
        <text>Analyses reveal that the addition of a virus component promotes the emergence of complex communities.
</text>
